## Category 2 — Spring Boot Questions

---

**Q7. What is Spring Boot?**

> "Spring Boot is a Java framework that makes it easy to create standalone, production-ready applications. It provides auto-configuration, embedded server, and many pre-built starters so you don't have to set up everything manually. You just add dependencies and start writing business logic."

---

**Q8. What is the difference between Spring and Spring Boot?**

> "Spring is the core framework but requires a lot of manual configuration — XML files, web server setup, etc. Spring Boot is built on top of Spring and provides auto-configuration, embedded Tomcat server, and starter dependencies. With Spring Boot you can start a web application in minutes without any XML configuration."

---

**Q9. What is @SpringBootApplication?**

> "It is the main annotation on the main class. It combines three annotations:
> - @Configuration — marks the class as a configuration class
> - @EnableAutoConfiguration — tells Spring Boot to auto-configure based on dependencies
> - @ComponentScan — scans all classes in the package for Spring components"

---

**Q10. What is @RestController?**

> "It combines @Controller and @ResponseBody. It marks a class as a REST API controller. Every method in this class automatically returns JSON response instead of a view page."

---

**Q11. What is the difference between @Controller and @RestController?**

> "@Controller is used for web MVC applications that return HTML views. @RestController is used for REST APIs that return JSON or XML data. @RestController = @Controller + @ResponseBody on every method."

---

**Q12. What annotations did you use on your controller methods?**

> - @PostMapping — for POST requests to create data
> - @GetMapping — for GET requests to read data
> - @PutMapping — for PUT requests to update data
> - @DeleteMapping — for DELETE requests to delete data
> - @PathVariable — to read values from the URL like /items/1
> - @RequestBody — to read the JSON body of the request
> - @RequestParam — to read query parameters like ?threshold=10

---

**Q13. What is @PathVariable vs @RequestParam?**

> "@PathVariable reads a value from the URL path itself. For example in /api/items/5, the 5 is a path variable. @RequestParam reads a value from the query string. For example in /api/inventory/low-stock?threshold=10, the threshold=10 is a request param."

---

**Q14. What is application.properties?**

> "It is the configuration file for a Spring Boot application. It contains settings like server port, database URL, username, password, JPA settings, JWT secret, and logging levels. Spring Boot reads this file automatically at startup."

---

**Q15. What is @Value annotation?**

> "It is used to inject values from application.properties into Java fields. For example:
> @Value('${jwt.secret}') private String secret;
> This reads the jwt.secret value from application.properties and puts it in the secret variable."

---

## Category 3 — REST API Questions

---

**Q16. What is REST API?**

> "REST stands for Representational State Transfer. It is a standard way of building web services. It uses HTTP methods — GET, POST, PUT, DELETE — to perform operations on resources. Data is exchanged in JSON format. Each URL represents a resource like /api/items represents the items resource."

---

**Q17. What are HTTP methods and when do you use each?**

> - POST — Create new data
> - GET — Read / fetch data
> - PUT — Update existing data completely
> - DELETE — Remove data
> - PATCH — Update partially (we used PUT which updates fully)

---

**Q18. What HTTP status codes did you use?**

> - 200 OK — successful GET, PUT, DELETE
> - 201 Created — successful POST (new record created)
> - 400 Bad Request — validation failed, wrong input
> - 401 Unauthorized — missing or invalid JWT token
> - 404 Not Found — record does not exist
> - 500 Internal Server Error — unexpected server error

---

**Q19. What is the difference between PUT and PATCH?**

> "PUT replaces the entire resource. You send all fields even if only one changed. PATCH updates only the fields you send. In our project we used PUT which means when updating an item you send all fields — name, description, category — and the entire record gets replaced with the new values."

---

**Q20. What is JSON?**

> "JSON stands for JavaScript Object Notation. It is a lightweight data format used to exchange data between client and server. It uses key-value pairs inside curly braces. Our APIs receive JSON as input and return JSON as output."

---

## Category 4 — JPA and Database Questions

---

**Q21. What is JPA?**

> "JPA stands for Java Persistence API. It is a specification that defines how Java objects should be mapped to database tables. Hibernate is the most popular implementation of JPA. With JPA you work with Java objects and it automatically generates SQL queries."

---

**Q22. What is Hibernate?**

> "Hibernate is an ORM — Object Relational Mapping — tool. It maps Java classes to database tables and Java fields to table columns. When you call save() on a repository, Hibernate generates the INSERT SQL. When you call findById(), it generates SELECT SQL. You don't write SQL manually."

---

**Q23. What is ORM?**

> "ORM stands for Object Relational Mapping. It is a technique to convert data between Java objects and database tables automatically. Instead of writing SQL, you work with Java objects. The ORM tool handles the conversion."

---

**Q24. What is @Entity?**

> "It marks a Java class as a database entity — meaning this class represents a database table. Every field in the class becomes a column in the table."

---

**Q25. What is @Table?**

> "It specifies the name of the database table that the entity maps to. For example @Table(name = 'items') means this class maps to the items table in MySQL."

---

**Q26. What is @Id and @GeneratedValue?**

> "@Id marks a field as the primary key of the table. @GeneratedValue with strategy IDENTITY means the database automatically generates the ID value — like AUTO_INCREMENT in MySQL. So you don't provide the ID when creating a record, MySQL assigns it automatically starting from 1."

---

**Q27. What is @Column?**

> "It is used to customize how a field maps to a database column. You can set the column name, whether it can be null, maximum length, etc. For example @Column(nullable = false, length = 150) means this column cannot be empty and max 150 characters."

---

**Q28. What is Spring Data JPA?**

> "Spring Data JPA is a layer on top of JPA that makes database operations even easier. You just create an interface that extends JpaRepository and you automatically get methods like save, findById, findAll, deleteById without writing any implementation code."

---

**Q29. What is JpaRepository?**

> "It is an interface provided by Spring Data JPA. When your repository extends JpaRepository, you get many ready-made methods for free — save, findById, findAll, deleteById, count, existsById and more. You don't need to implement any of them."

---

**Q30. How does Spring generate SQL from method names?**

> "Spring Data JPA reads the method name and generates SQL automatically. For example:
> - findByCategory → SELECT * FROM items WHERE category = ?
> - findByNameContainingIgnoreCase → SELECT * FROM items WHERE LOWER(name) LIKE LOWER('%?%')
> - existsByNameAndCategory → SELECT COUNT(*) FROM items WHERE name=? AND category=?
> This feature is called Query Derivation."

---

**Q31. What is @Transactional?**

> "It ensures that a set of database operations either all succeed or all fail together. This is called atomicity. If any operation inside the transaction fails, all previous operations in that transaction are rolled back so the database stays in a consistent state. In our service methods, @Transactional ensures data integrity."

---

**Q32. What is ddl-auto=update in application.properties?**

> "It tells Hibernate what to do with the database schema at startup. Update means Hibernate will look at the entity classes and automatically create tables if they don't exist, or add new columns if you added new fields. It never drops existing data."

