## Category 5 — Architecture Questions

---

**Q33. What is layered architecture?**

> "It is a way of organizing code where each layer has a specific responsibility. Our project has 5 layers:
> - Controller — receives requests
> - Service — business logic
> - Repository — database operations
> - Model — database table representation
> - DTO — data transfer between client and server
> Each layer only talks to the layer directly below it."

---

**Q34. What is the difference between Model and DTO?**

> "Model represents the database table and is used internally for database operations. DTO is used to transfer data between client and server through the API. They are kept separate so you can control what data gets exposed, add validation rules, and change the database structure without breaking the API."

---

**Q35. What is the Service layer and why is it needed?**

> "The Service layer contains the business logic. It sits between the Controller and Repository. Keeping business logic in the service layer means the controller stays thin — it just receives and returns data. The service decides how to process the data, what rules to apply, and what operations to perform. This makes the code cleaner and easier to test."

---

**Q36. What is the Repository layer?**

> "The Repository layer is responsible for all database operations. It is the only layer that directly talks to the database. By keeping database operations in one place, if you change the database later — for example from MySQL to PostgreSQL — you only change the repository layer, nothing else."

---

**Q37. Why do you have separate databases for each service?**

> "This is a key principle of microservice architecture called database per service. With separate databases each service is truly independent. One service cannot break another service's database. Each service can also choose the best database type for its needs. And if one database goes down only that one service is affected."

---

## Category 6 — Security Questions

---

**Q38. What is JWT?**

> "JWT stands for JSON Web Token. It is a compact, self-contained token used for authentication. It has three parts separated by dots — Header, Payload, and Signature. The header contains the algorithm used. The payload contains user information. The signature is used to verify the token hasn't been tampered with."

---

**Q39. How does JWT work in your project?**

> "When a request comes in, the JwtAuthFilter intercepts it before it reaches the controller. It reads the Authorization header and extracts the Bearer token. It then validates the token using the secret key with JwtUtil. If valid, the request proceeds. If invalid or missing, a 401 Unauthorized response is returned immediately."

---

**Q40. What is the difference between Authentication and Authorization?**

> "Authentication is proving who you are — like showing your ID. Authorization is proving what you are allowed to do — like showing your access level badge. In our project, JWT handles authentication — proving the caller has a valid token. Authorization would be checking if that user has permission to perform a specific action."

---

**Q41. What is Spring Security?**

> "Spring Security is a framework that handles authentication and authorization in Spring applications. In our project we use it to intercept all incoming requests, integrate our JWT filter, and define which URLs are public and which require authentication."

---

**Q42. What is SecurityFilterChain?**

> "It is a Spring Security configuration that defines security rules. In our project we configured it to disable CSRF (not needed for REST APIs), use stateless sessions (no server-side session storage), allow Swagger URLs without authentication, and require JWT token for all other URLs."

---

**Q43. What is CSRF and why did you disable it?**

> "CSRF stands for Cross-Site Request Forgery. It is a security attack relevant to browser-based form submissions with session cookies. Since our project is a REST API using JWT tokens (not cookies), CSRF protection is not needed. That is why we disabled it."

---

**Q44. What is Stateless session?**

> "Stateless means the server does not store any session information about the client. Every request must carry all necessary information — in our case the JWT token. The server validates the token on every request independently. This is better for scalability because any server instance can handle any request."

---

## Category 7 — Validation and Error Handling Questions

---

**Q45. How did you implement validation?**

> "I used Spring's @Valid annotation with Bean Validation annotations in the DTO classes. Annotations like @NotBlank ensure a field is not empty, @Size sets length limits, @Email validates email format, @Min ensures a number is above a minimum value. When a request comes in, Spring automatically validates the DTO and returns a 400 error if any rule fails."

---

**Q46. What validation annotations did you use?**

> - @NotBlank — field must not be null or empty
> - @NotNull — field must not be null
> - @Size(max=150) — string length must not exceed 150
> - @Email — must be a valid email format
> - @Min(value=0) — number must be 0 or more

---

**Q47. What is GlobalExceptionHandler?**

> "It is a class annotated with @RestControllerAdvice that handles all exceptions across the entire application. Instead of each controller handling its own errors, the GlobalExceptionHandler catches all exceptions in one place and returns consistent, clean JSON error responses. No stack traces are exposed to clients."

---

**Q48. What is @RestControllerAdvice?**

> "It is an annotation that marks a class as a global exception handler for all REST controllers. Any exception thrown anywhere in the application gets caught here and converted to a proper HTTP response with appropriate status code and message."

---

**Q49. What is @ExceptionHandler?**

> "It marks a method inside GlobalExceptionHandler as the handler for a specific exception type. For example @ExceptionHandler(ItemNotFoundException.class) means that method will run whenever an ItemNotFoundException is thrown anywhere in the application."

---

## Category 8 — Lombok Questions

---

**Q50. What is Lombok and why did you use it?**

> "Lombok is a Java library that reduces boilerplate code. Instead of writing getters, setters, constructors, toString, equals, hashCode manually, you just add annotations. @Data generates getters and setters, @NoArgsConstructor generates a no-argument constructor, @AllArgsConstructor generates a constructor with all fields, @Builder gives a builder pattern for creating objects."

---

**Q51. What Lombok annotations did you use?**

> - @Data — generates getters, setters, toString, equals, hashCode
> - @NoArgsConstructor — generates empty constructor
> - @AllArgsConstructor — generates constructor with all fields
> - @Builder — generates builder pattern
> - @RequiredArgsConstructor — generates constructor for final fields
> - @Slf4j — generates a logger variable automatically

---

## Category 9 — Testing Questions

---

**Q52. What types of testing did you do?**

> "I wrote unit tests for the service layer using JUnit 5 and Mockito. Unit tests test individual components in isolation without a real database or running server."

---

**Q53. What is Mockito?**

> "Mockito is a Java mocking framework. In unit tests you don't want to use a real database because tests should be fast and independent. Mockito lets you create fake versions of dependencies. For example instead of a real ItemRepository hitting MySQL, you create a mock that returns predefined data."

---

**Q54. What is the difference between Unit Test and Integration Test?**

> "Unit tests test a single class or method in isolation. Dependencies are mocked. They run very fast. Integration tests test multiple components working together — like controller calling service calling real database. They are slower but test the full flow. In our project we have unit tests for the service layer."

---

**Q55. What is @ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)?**

> "It tells JUnit to use Mockito as the test extension. This enables Mockito annotations like @Mock and @InjectMocks to work automatically without manually calling MockitoAnnotations.openMocks()."

---

**Q56. What is @Mock and @InjectMocks?**

> "@Mock creates a fake version of a class. @InjectMocks creates the real class being tested and automatically injects all @Mock objects into it. For example @Mock ItemRepository creates a fake repository. @InjectMocks ItemServiceImpl creates the real service and injects the fake repository into it."

---

**Q57. What is the difference between when().thenReturn() and verify()?**

> "when().thenReturn() sets up what a mock should return when a specific method is called — this is called stubbing. verify() checks that a specific method was actually called during the test. For example verify(itemRepository, times(1)).save(any()) checks that save was called exactly once."

---

## Category 10 — Swagger Questions

---

**Q58. What is Swagger?**

> "Swagger is an API documentation tool. SpringDoc OpenAPI reads the controller annotations and automatically generates interactive API documentation. Developers can open the Swagger UI in browser, see all endpoints, understand what JSON to send, and test APIs directly without needing Postman."

---

**Q59. What annotations did you use for Swagger?**

> - @Tag — gives a name and description to a controller group
> - @Operation — describes what a specific endpoint does
> - These appear as labels in the Swagger UI

---

## Category 11 — Maven Questions

---

**Q60. What is Maven?**

> "Maven is a build tool for Java projects. It manages dependencies — you list what libraries you need in pom.xml and Maven downloads them automatically. It also compiles the code, runs tests, and packages the application into a JAR file."

---

**Q61. What is pom.xml?**

> "POM stands for Project Object Model. It is the configuration file for Maven. It contains the project details, Java version, and all dependencies the project needs. When you run the project, Maven reads pom.xml and downloads all required libraries."

---

**Q62. What is a dependency in Maven?**

> "A dependency is an external library your project needs. Instead of downloading JAR files manually, you declare them in pom.xml with groupId, artifactId, and version. Maven automatically downloads them from the internet and makes them available in your project."

---

## Category 12 — Tricky Questions

---

**Q63. What happens if two services try to modify the same item at the same time?**

> "In our current implementation each service has its own database so they don't directly conflict. Within one service, @Transactional ensures database consistency. In a production system you would implement optimistic locking using @Version annotation which adds a version column to the table and prevents conflicting updates."

---

**Q64. How would services communicate with each other in production?**

> "There are two ways. Synchronous communication using REST template or Feign Client — one service directly calls another service's API and waits for the response. Asynchronous communication using message queues like RabbitMQ or Kafka — one service publishes an event and other services consume it independently. Async is preferred for better resilience."

---

**Q65. What would you improve in this project?**

> "I would add:
> - API Gateway to have a single entry point for all services
> - Service Discovery using Eureka so services can find each other automatically
> - Centralized configuration using Spring Cloud Config
> - Message queue like Kafka for async communication between services
> - Docker containers for easy deployment
> - Circuit breaker pattern using Resilience4j to handle service failures gracefully"

---

**Q66. What is an API Gateway?**

> "An API Gateway is a single entry point for all client requests. Instead of clients knowing about 4 different ports (8081, 8082, 8083, 8084), they only talk to the gateway. The gateway routes requests to the correct service. It can also handle authentication, rate limiting, and load balancing centrally."

---

**Q67. What is the difference between @Component, @Service, @Repository?**

> "All three are specializations of @Component — they all register the class as a Spring bean. The difference is semantic meaning:
> - @Component — generic Spring component
> - @Service — marks a class as service layer, business logic
> - @Repository — marks a class as data access layer, also adds exception translation for database errors"

---

**Q68. What is dependency injection?**

> "Dependency Injection means Spring creates and manages objects for you and injects them where needed. Instead of creating objects manually with new keyword, you declare what you need and Spring provides it. In our project @RequiredArgsConstructor with final fields tells Spring to inject the required dependencies through the constructor automatically."

---

**Q69. What is the difference between @Autowired and @RequiredArgsConstructor?**

> "@Autowired directly injects dependencies into fields. @RequiredArgsConstructor is a Lombok annotation that generates a constructor for all final fields and Spring uses constructor injection. Constructor injection is preferred because it makes dependencies explicit, easier to test, and the object is always in a valid state."

---

**Q70. What would happen if you start two instances of Item Service?**

> "Both instances would connect to the same item_db database. Requests could be handled by either instance which is good for load balancing. However you would need a load balancer in front to distribute traffic, and a service registry like Eureka so other services know about both instances."

